should be very big fans of the work that we're doing as well.

52
00:02:31,451 --> 00:02:32,272
So this is just a quick look at Yo!World.

53
00:02:36,305 --> 00:02:39,026
Your World is an online social decorating and dress-up game.

54
00:02:39,026 --> 00:02:42,348
As of right now, we have around 75,000 daily active users,

55
00:02:42,348 --> 00:02:43,588
about 200,000 MAU.

56
00:02:43,588 --> 00:02:48,670
Obviously, the numbers shift month to month based on current market trends,

57
00:02:48,670 --> 00:02:50,831
but that's our general average number.

58
00:02:50,831 --> 00:02:54,512
The game was actually created by one of our founders back in 2011,

59
00:02:54,512 --> 00:02:58,693
and it had been in operation for about a year and a half when it was sold off to Zynga.

60
00:02:59,655 --> 00:03:03,697
And after years of success, Zynga did a wonderful job with it,

61
00:03:03,697 --> 00:03:05,678
the game was no longer a priority for Zynga.

62
00:03:05,678 --> 00:03:09,119
As the owners of the game and it being a smaller title,

63
00:03:09,119 --> 00:03:10,820
they had basically bigger fish to fry.

64
00:03:10,820 --> 00:03:13,421
It wasn't turning the profit that they would want it to turn,

65
00:03:13,421 --> 00:03:15,462
didn't make sense in their portfolio.

66
00:03:15,462 --> 00:03:19,304
Perfectly logical conclusion for a large company,

67
00:03:19,304 --> 00:03:21,465
but what they didn't necessarily anticipate

68
00:03:21,465 --> 00:03:23,005
was that they had a highly engaged.

69
00:03:23,922 --> 00:03:25,824
rabid and vocal fan base.

70
00:03:25,824 --> 00:03:30,749
So what happened for us is that when they were going to sunset the title,

71
00:03:30,749 --> 00:03:31,810
the players reached out to us.

72
00:03:31,810 --> 00:03:33,772
And what they said was,

73
00:03:33,772 --> 00:03:36,074
we love this game, can you do anything to save us?

74
00:03:36,074 --> 00:03:40,038
Because we are desperate to keep playing this game. We have years invested in

75
00:03:40,038 --> 00:03:44,662
social relationships and money and just friends and everything else.

76
00:03:44,662 --> 00:03:45,363
And so we did.

77
00:03:48,117 --> 00:03:53,842
So, falling on deaf ears is part of the important takeaway

78
00:03:53,842 --> 00:03:54,262
for our talk today.

79
00:03:54,262 --> 00:03:57,745
One of the things that happened when dealing

80
00:03:57,745 --> 00:04:00,368
with the previous owners is that players submitted

81
00:04:00,368 --> 00:04:01,909
numerous complaints over and over again,

82
00:04:01,909 --> 00:04:06,713
but the developer chose not to listen to them,

83
00:04:06,713 --> 00:04:08,154
partially because they weren't a priority

84
00:04:08,154 --> 00:04:09,736
and partially because they had their own agenda.

85
00:04:09,736 --> 00:04:12,878
One of the major things that happened was

86
00:04:13,369 --> 00:04:15,470
Security vulnerabilities are a very real thing.

87
00:04:15,470 --> 00:04:19,273
Anybody who deals with Flash games knows it's Flash.

88
00:04:19,273 --> 00:04:20,554
It has security vulnerabilities.

89
00:04:20,554 --> 00:04:22,035
What are you going to do?

90
00:04:22,035 --> 00:04:23,536
So malicious cash injection actually

91
00:04:23,536 --> 00:04:27,019
became a very big problem for the game.

92
00:04:27,019 --> 00:04:30,802
Malicious parties actually managed to get into the game,

93
00:04:30,802 --> 00:04:32,964
put hard currency into the game, and at that point,

94
00:04:32,964 --> 00:04:35,145
what is the purpose of a player supporting the game?

95
00:04:35,145 --> 00:04:36,686
Why would you buy currency when you can just

96
00:04:36,686 --> 00:04:39,228
get it from some random guy off the internet for free, right?

97
00:04:40,217 --> 00:04:43,019
One of the secondary results of that is that item quality

98
00:04:43,019 --> 00:04:45,100
took a dive, and in a massive way.

99
00:04:45,100 --> 00:04:48,203
As a hugely content-driven game,

100
00:04:48,203 --> 00:04:50,604
your world depends very much on its content economy.

101
00:04:50,604 --> 00:04:55,048
So because the profitability of the game was diving,

102
00:04:55,048 --> 00:04:57,329
they were looking for ways to cut costs on item creation.

103
00:04:57,329 --> 00:04:59,791
One of the ways you can cut costs on item creation

104
00:04:59,791 --> 00:05:00,852
is outsourcing.

105
00:05:00,852 --> 00:05:03,614
This is not, I want to be really clear,

106
00:05:03,614 --> 00:05:04,575
this is not bad-mouthing outsourcing.

107
00:05:04,575 --> 00:05:06,796
There are a lot of great outsourcing firms in the world.

108
00:05:07,488 --> 00:05:09,570
but there are also very inexpensive ones

109
00:05:09,570 --> 00:05:10,811
and you tend to get what you pay for.

110
00:05:10,811 --> 00:05:14,214
And that was the case that we had with Yo! World.

111
00:05:14,214 --> 00:05:17,637
So it started becoming a self-fulfilling prophecy.

112
00:05:17,637 --> 00:05:20,039
As a result of the item quality going down,

113
00:05:20,039 --> 00:05:22,842
the malicious cast injection, players started to leave.

114
00:05:22,842 --> 00:05:23,742
When you have players leaving,

115
00:05:23,742 --> 00:05:25,844
you have less players supporting,

116
00:05:25,844 --> 00:05:27,706
you make less and less good quality items

117
00:05:27,706 --> 00:05:29,568
because it can't be justified monetarily.

118
00:05:30,961 --> 00:05:32,802
And this is where we get to the point of not listening

119
00:05:32,802 --> 00:05:34,703
to players can kill your game.

120
00:05:34,703 --> 00:05:36,904
It's really important to recognize that players

121
00:05:36,904 --> 00:05:39,945
have a voice and that they matter.

122
00:05:39,945 --> 00:05:43,087
They're really the lifeblood of every single game

123
00:05:43,087 --> 00:05:45,328
that we work on.

124
00:05:45,328 --> 00:05:48,509
So listening to them is the most important thing

125
00:05:48,509 --> 00:05:49,089
that you can do.

126
00:05:49,089 --> 00:05:52,411
The lack of listening and response is actually

127
00:05:52,411 --> 00:05:54,572
one of the biggest reasons that Yo!Ville,

128
00:05:54,572 --> 00:05:56,133
now Yo!World, almost died.

129
00:05:56,133 --> 00:05:58,094
So players are people too.

130
00:06:01,494 --> 00:06:03,496
Players are a lot more than just dollar signs

131
00:06:03,496 --> 00:06:04,216
and data points.

132
00:06:04,216 --> 00:06:08,860
One of the things that I noticed a couple years ago at GDC

133
00:06:08,860 --> 00:06:11,062
was I went to a monetization roundtable

134
00:06:11,062 --> 00:06:14,004
and the direction that the conversation went about players

135
00:06:14,004 --> 00:06:16,486
made me seriously question what I was doing with my career.

136
00:06:16,486 --> 00:06:19,929
Because there were people talking about price anchoring

137
00:06:19,929 --> 00:06:23,271
and psychological matrices and how you can trick players

138
00:06:23,271 --> 00:06:24,392
into spending more money.

139
00:06:24,392 --> 00:06:27,574
And I started questioning sort of what has happened

140
00:06:27,574 --> 00:06:28,896
to us as developers.

141
00:06:29,635 --> 00:06:32,037
when every single person who got into games

142
00:06:32,037 --> 00:06:33,859
got into games because we love games.

143
00:06:33,859 --> 00:06:35,740
So why would we possibly treat people

144
00:06:35,740 --> 00:06:38,623
who share that love with us any differently

145
00:06:38,623 --> 00:06:40,044
than we'd want to be treated ourselves, right?

146
00:06:40,044 --> 00:06:43,386
Our players are unique and interesting people.

147
00:06:44,317 --> 00:06:46,218
and they're all craving great experiences.

148
00:06:46,218 --> 00:06:48,039
And we can deliver those experiences,

149
00:06:48,039 --> 00:06:50,401
especially with the player's input.

150
00:06:50,401 --> 00:06:51,722
So how do we go about doing that?

151
00:06:51,722 --> 00:06:53,263
Well, first of all, we need to recognize

152
00:06:53,263 --> 00:06:56,585
that there is far more of them than there are of us.

153
00:06:56,585 --> 00:06:58,246
And that can be, especially at GDC,

154
00:06:58,246 --> 00:06:59,687
that can be a tough thing to realize

155
00:06:59,687 --> 00:07:01,829
because there's so many devs here.

156
00:07:01,829 --> 00:07:02,950
But if we're putting it into context,

157
00:07:02,950 --> 00:07:05,471
just a little bit of a visual aid.

158
00:07:05,471 --> 00:07:06,332
So if we take a look at the size

159
00:07:06,332 --> 00:07:08,093
of the Yo! World development team

160
00:07:08,093 --> 00:07:10,115
versus what we like to call the player team,

161
00:07:10,115 --> 00:07:12,316
if you put them side by side,

162
00:07:13,055 --> 00:07:14,276
They look close to equal.

163
00:07:14,276 --> 00:07:16,757
But then you realize that there's more players,

164
00:07:16,757 --> 00:07:18,679
and there's more players,

165
00:07:18,679 --> 00:07:21,841
and there's not another slide full of people

166
00:07:21,841 --> 00:07:23,783
because I could do it for about another 100,000 slides.

167
00:07:23,783 --> 00:07:26,305
But there's so many of them,

168
00:07:26,305 --> 00:07:27,706
why wouldn't we take advantage

169
00:07:27,706 --> 00:07:29,667
of that great information and feedback loop

170
00:07:29,667 --> 00:07:31,949
that we can use to improve the quality of our games

171
00:07:31,949 --> 00:07:33,890
and improve the quality of our work?

172
00:07:33,890 --> 00:07:36,052
So just to put the numbers

173
00:07:36,052 --> 00:07:37,413
into a little bit of perspective for you.

174
00:07:38,576 --> 00:07:43,621
One tester in one day of work can do about eight hours of testing exposure.

175
00:07:43,621 --> 00:07:46,064
And we're not going to get into ideal man hours or anything like that.

176
00:07:46,064 --> 00:07:49,088
Let's just assume that one person works eight hours in a day for the sake of simplicity.

177
00:07:49,088 --> 00:07:54,894
But 50,000 players playing your game in the first five minutes can do over 4,000 hours

178
00:07:54,894 --> 00:07:55,455
of testing.

179
00:07:56,175 --> 00:08:01,380
So that's a powerful thing because that's 520 workdays of testing in the first five minutes.

180
00:08:01,380 --> 00:08:07,264
So when you realize, one, you have people who are really engaged and really interested in helping improve the quality of your game,

181
00:08:07,264 --> 00:08:13,930
and two, that there's a lot of them, you can leverage that to actually help your business grow inexpensively

182
00:08:13,930 --> 00:08:17,933
while making the players happy because they have a voice in the destiny of the product.

183
00:08:17,933 --> 00:08:18,994
It's a really powerful thing.

184
00:08:21,962 --> 00:08:27,327
So I'm going to talk a little bit about what our first steps were when recovering the game.

185
00:08:28,150 --> 00:08:33,095
Your World, as I mentioned, was a game that had some serious trust issues with the previous

186
00:08:33,095 --> 00:08:38,960
ownership, partially just due to lack of sun setting and players having sort of gone away

187
00:08:38,960 --> 00:08:39,741
in droves.

188
00:08:39,741 --> 00:08:43,825
So the first thing that we did when we took the game back was we sat down and we had a

189
00:08:43,825 --> 00:08:48,349
conversation about how we were going to reengage this group of players and how we were going

190
00:08:48,349 --> 00:08:49,931
to have this conversation with them.

191
00:08:49,931 --> 00:08:53,554
What could we possibly do to re-earn the trust of people who...

192
00:08:54,256 --> 00:08:56,458
felt like they had been abused for years, right?

193
00:08:56,458 --> 00:08:57,359
That's a very hard thing.

194
00:08:57,359 --> 00:09:00,122
So the first thing that we did was we sat down

195
00:09:00,122 --> 00:09:01,764
and we created what you see up on the screen there,

196
00:09:01,764 --> 00:09:03,345
which is our three pillars.

197
00:09:03,345 --> 00:09:05,267
And our three pillars for our players

198
00:09:05,267 --> 00:09:07,830
are number one, safe and secure,

199
00:09:07,830 --> 00:09:09,031
number two, community engagement,

200
00:09:09,031 --> 00:09:11,113
and number three, player-made experiences.

201
00:09:11,113 --> 00:09:12,875
And I'll go into those in a little bit more detail.

202
00:09:12,875 --> 00:09:15,318
Safe and secure is fairly straightforward.

203
00:09:15,736 --> 00:09:18,697
When you think about the issue of malicious cash injection into a game,

204
00:09:18,697 --> 00:09:24,380
especially a game that is a virtual economy that thrives on the buying, selling, and trading of goods,

205
00:09:24,380 --> 00:09:28,822
it becomes very important to realize that the safety and security of that system is paramount.

206
00:09:28,822 --> 00:09:30,543
It's higher than anything else.

207
00:09:30,543 --> 00:09:35,205
If you can't sell people goods and allow them to support the game, the game's going to die.

208
00:09:35,966 --> 00:09:38,327
Secondarily, as a highly social game,

209
00:09:38,327 --> 00:09:39,848
it's really important to recognize

210
00:09:39,848 --> 00:09:41,609
that people who are playing in a social context,

211
00:09:41,609 --> 00:09:44,711
especially Facebook or any other social network,

212
00:09:44,711 --> 00:09:47,593
are deeply concerned about their own security and privacy.

213
00:09:47,593 --> 00:09:48,994
You need to be able to guarantee

214
00:09:48,994 --> 00:09:50,155
that security and privacy for them.

215
00:09:50,155 --> 00:09:51,716
Otherwise, they're not going to trust you

216
00:09:51,716 --> 00:09:53,998
and they're gonna find somebody or someone else to go to.

217
00:09:53,998 --> 00:09:59,281
So the second of our pillars is community engagement.

218
00:09:59,281 --> 00:10:02,183
Also fairly straightforward, but very, very important.

219
00:10:03,460 --> 00:10:06,323
We made a commitment to our players from day one

220
00:10:06,323 --> 00:10:08,244
that we would engage them in the conversation

221
00:10:08,244 --> 00:10:08,845
every step of the way,

222
00:10:08,845 --> 00:10:10,866
that they were always going to be part.

223
00:10:10,866 --> 00:10:13,608
And what this means for us

224
00:10:13,608 --> 00:10:17,752
is that we've created forms of feedback

225
00:10:17,752 --> 00:10:20,073
and different avenues of communication

226
00:10:20,073 --> 00:10:21,815
so that players always have a say

227
00:10:21,815 --> 00:10:23,056
in the direction that the game's going,

228
00:10:23,056 --> 00:10:25,317
which sounds very, very scary to a lot of people.

229
00:10:26,056 --> 00:10:28,837
because who's steering the ship, right?

230
00:10:28,837 --> 00:10:31,359
Well, as a developer, you are ultimately steering the ship,

231
00:10:31,359 --> 00:10:33,520
but you have to remember that the players

232
00:10:33,520 --> 00:10:35,761
are the waves on which your ship crests, right?

233
00:10:35,761 --> 00:10:39,503
They are the crux of everything that you do,

234
00:10:39,503 --> 00:10:40,643
so you can't forget that.

235
00:10:40,643 --> 00:10:43,345
And finally, player-made experiences.

236
00:10:45,399 --> 00:10:47,981
This one's a little bit more tricky

237
00:10:47,981 --> 00:10:51,443
in the way that it works, but essentially,

238
00:10:51,443 --> 00:10:53,364
the way that Your World works as a game,

239
00:10:53,364 --> 00:10:55,085
because it is a design and dress-up game

240
00:10:55,085 --> 00:10:57,626
and a social game, players rely very much

241
00:10:57,626 --> 00:10:59,127
on the ability to build things

242
00:10:59,127 --> 00:11:00,488
and show them to other players.

243
00:11:00,488 --> 00:11:02,289
It's very important for them to be able

244
00:11:02,289 --> 00:11:04,310
to activate their own creativity

245
00:11:04,310 --> 00:11:06,091
and show that to the rest of the people

246
00:11:06,091 --> 00:11:07,972
who are playing the game.

247
00:11:07,972 --> 00:11:11,914
So what this means for us is we create things

248
00:11:12,715 --> 00:11:16,198
quite often feature-wise, roughly 60% of the way.

249
00:11:16,198 --> 00:11:18,000
And we let players fill in the other 40%.

250
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:22,144
So whether it be a feature that allows

251
00:11:22,144 --> 00:11:24,506
for user-generated content to be piped in

252
00:11:24,506 --> 00:11:26,448
and then shared with other users,

253
00:11:26,448 --> 00:11:29,151
or a first iteration of a feature

254
00:11:29,151 --> 00:11:31,573
that then goes out to players, gets feedback,

255
00:11:31,573 --> 00:11:34,756
and then we build another 20% based on that feedback,

256
00:11:34,756 --> 00:11:36,718
we bring them along the journey every step of the way.

257
00:11:40,171 --> 00:11:42,173
So, in terms of regaining players' trust,

258
00:11:42,173 --> 00:11:45,055
the pillars were really important for us

259
00:11:45,055 --> 00:11:48,638
in that they created a touchstone for us,

260
00:11:48,638 --> 00:11:50,980
and that touchstone has been important

261
00:11:50,980 --> 00:11:55,064
for the last three years of owning the game, essentially.

262
00:11:55,064 --> 00:11:57,446
We refer to them very frequently in our player discussions.

263
00:11:57,446 --> 00:11:59,227
We refer to them very frequently

264
00:11:59,227 --> 00:12:00,168
in our in-house discussions.

265
00:12:00,168 --> 00:12:02,109
When we're doing feature design,

266
00:12:02,109 --> 00:12:04,571
the first thing that we do is we go back

267
00:12:04,975 --> 00:12:06,676
to that first pillar, right?

268
00:12:06,676 --> 00:12:09,796
We say, okay, is this feature gonna be safe and secure?

269
00:12:09,796 --> 00:12:11,757
Is it going to be something that we can guarantee

270
00:12:11,757 --> 00:12:15,278
there's going to be no security flaws with whatsoever?

271
00:12:15,278 --> 00:12:19,999
We've spent the last three years fighting off

272
00:12:19,999 --> 00:12:22,259
very persistent people who it's,

273
00:12:22,259 --> 00:12:25,120
I don't know where they got this mission from,

274
00:12:25,120 --> 00:12:28,401
but it is their God-given mission to infiltrate the game.

275
00:12:28,401 --> 00:12:29,321
And in the last three years,

276
00:12:29,321 --> 00:12:31,741
we haven't had a single major security incident,

277
00:12:31,741 --> 00:12:33,002
which is a point of pride,

278
00:12:33,002 --> 00:12:34,902
and that's because we use these touchstones.

279
00:12:36,483 --> 00:12:38,623
So every single time we do a feature,

280
00:12:38,623 --> 00:12:40,564
we ask one, is it safe and secure?

281
00:12:40,564 --> 00:12:41,745
Two, how does it engage the community?

282
00:12:41,745 --> 00:12:45,126
Does it engage the community in a meaningful way

283
00:12:45,126 --> 00:12:48,347
or is it just paying lip service to that engagement?

284
00:12:48,347 --> 00:12:50,728
And then how is it allowing players

285
00:12:50,728 --> 00:12:51,908
to generate their own experience?

286
00:12:51,908 --> 00:12:52,628
Now don't get me wrong,

287
00:12:52,628 --> 00:12:55,829
not every feature can generate experiences for players.

288
00:12:55,829 --> 00:12:57,890
You can't allow players to generate all of the content,

289
00:12:57,890 --> 00:13:00,491
but allowing them to generate a lot of it

290
00:13:00,491 --> 00:13:01,211
is really important.

291
00:13:05,380 --> 00:13:07,221
So one of the important things to remember

292
00:13:07,221 --> 00:13:08,642
is that the industry is evolving,

293
00:13:08,642 --> 00:13:11,863
and player expectations are not what they used to be.

294
00:13:11,863 --> 00:13:13,124
And that's something,

295
00:13:13,124 --> 00:13:14,764
I've been around the industry for a while,

296
00:13:14,764 --> 00:13:16,425
and that's something that I've definitely noticed,

297
00:13:16,425 --> 00:13:18,306
particularly in the last five years,

298
00:13:18,306 --> 00:13:21,367
is that the savviness of players has gone way up.

299
00:13:21,367 --> 00:13:22,488
Players are onto us,

300
00:13:22,488 --> 00:13:26,269
especially when it comes to pricing strategy

301
00:13:26,269 --> 00:13:29,491
and how we approach microtransactions and things like DLC.

302
00:13:30,211 --> 00:13:31,652
There are goods and bads to this.

303
00:13:31,652 --> 00:13:33,413
Some players actually understand that yes,

304
00:13:33,413 --> 00:13:36,134
ultimately we are running businesses

305
00:13:36,134 --> 00:13:38,775
and we have families to feed and that's a great thing,

306
00:13:38,775 --> 00:13:40,516
but at the same time, they will jump on top of you

307
00:13:40,516 --> 00:13:41,957
if they feel like you're taking advantage of them.

308
00:13:41,957 --> 00:13:44,438
And the second thing here is that the marketplace

309
00:13:44,438 --> 00:13:46,339
is a lot noisier than it used to be.

310
00:13:46,339 --> 00:13:49,040
This is a good thing for a lot of indie developers

311
00:13:49,040 --> 00:13:52,122
in that it's easier to be an entrant into the market

312
00:13:52,862 --> 00:13:54,524
but it's harder to succeed in the market.

313
00:13:54,524 --> 00:13:57,146
Because there's so many people who are now competing

314
00:13:57,146 --> 00:14:00,228
in all of these spaces, whether it be the Google Play Store

315
00:14:00,228 --> 00:14:01,289
or the App Store or Steam,

316
00:14:01,289 --> 00:14:03,511
there's so many people doing independent development,

317
00:14:03,511 --> 00:14:04,712
which is awesome and exciting,

318
00:14:04,712 --> 00:14:06,734
but there's so many of them, how do you break through?

319
00:14:06,734 --> 00:14:08,135
So we need to find ways to cut through,

320
00:14:08,135 --> 00:14:10,277
and one of the ways that you can actually do that

321
00:14:10,277 --> 00:14:11,998
is engaging your players directly

322
00:14:11,998 --> 00:14:14,000
and making them part of the conversation.

323
00:14:16,032 --> 00:14:18,154
So I'm gonna talk a little bit about some of the stuff

324
00:14:18,154 --> 00:14:20,536
that we do to engage our players

325
00:14:20,536 --> 00:14:22,899
and get feedback from them in a meaningful manner

326
00:14:22,899 --> 00:14:24,380
that we can actually make use of.

327
00:14:24,380 --> 00:14:28,044
The bread and butter for us, quite frankly,

328
00:14:28,044 --> 00:14:30,486
is the demographic survey.

329
00:14:30,486 --> 00:14:32,188
How many people here have used

330
00:14:32,188 --> 00:14:33,829
demographic surveys in their game?

331
00:14:33,829 --> 00:14:36,072
Okay, so some, not a lot.

332
00:14:36,072 --> 00:14:39,015
If you've got a LiveOps game.

333
00:14:40,088 --> 00:14:42,249
and you don't know the demographic of your game,

334
00:14:42,249 --> 00:14:43,911
you need to really seriously reconsider

335
00:14:43,911 --> 00:14:45,092
the way that you're approaching your players.

336
00:14:45,092 --> 00:14:47,253
Because if you don't know who they are,

337
00:14:47,253 --> 00:14:49,215
how are you possibly gonna know what they want?

338
00:14:49,215 --> 00:14:51,277
You're just shooting in the dark.

339
00:14:51,277 --> 00:14:55,020
One of the really interesting things that we have learned

340
00:14:55,020 --> 00:14:57,662
by way of our demographic survey is that in your world,

341
00:14:57,662 --> 00:14:59,143
70% of our players are actually female.

342
00:14:59,143 --> 00:15:03,547
Which makes us have a very, very unique demographic.

343
00:15:04,175 --> 00:15:07,759
One of the challenges, and lots of people can attest to this,

344
00:15:07,759 --> 00:15:11,623
is the industry itself does tend to be very male-dominated.

345
00:15:11,623 --> 00:15:13,585
So how do we break through?

346
00:15:13,585 --> 00:15:16,108
How do we break that barrier of having a highly

347
00:15:16,108 --> 00:15:21,094
female-driven player base while still making sure

348
00:15:21,094 --> 00:15:24,017
that our people are making things that they want to make?

349
00:15:24,017 --> 00:15:25,799
Well, one of the things that we do

350
00:15:26,661 --> 00:15:30,764
internally is we actually make sure that we actively hire

351
00:15:30,764 --> 00:15:32,525
as many females as we possibly can.

352
00:15:32,525 --> 00:15:35,468
And the reason for that is if you're dealing

353
00:15:35,468 --> 00:15:37,229
with a largely female base, then you should have

354
00:15:37,229 --> 00:15:39,070
as many females on the team as possible.

355
00:15:39,070 --> 00:15:42,633
The second thing that we do, and this is really important,

356
00:15:42,633 --> 00:15:46,996
is we never assume that any person fits a stereotype.

357
00:15:46,996 --> 00:15:49,938
So if you say, you know, 70% of the players are female,

358
00:15:49,938 --> 00:15:52,640
we need more female content, what does that possibly mean?

359
00:15:53,311 --> 00:15:55,111
That doesn't mean anything.

360
00:15:55,111 --> 00:15:57,712
That means that whatever assumption that you've generated

361
00:15:57,712 --> 00:16:00,513
about what female-generated content is,

362
00:16:00,513 --> 00:16:02,014
is what you're gonna push on them.

363
00:16:02,014 --> 00:16:03,794
But what you should actually be doing is saying,

364
00:16:03,794 --> 00:16:06,295
okay, now that we know that there's 70% of the players

365
00:16:06,295 --> 00:16:08,996
that are female, let's send out a survey

366
00:16:08,996 --> 00:16:11,476
to our female players and ask them

367
00:16:11,476 --> 00:16:12,617
what it is that they want.

368
00:16:12,617 --> 00:16:14,877
And then when they tell you, you can better deliver

369
00:16:14,877 --> 00:16:16,178
to them what they actually want.

370
00:16:16,843 --> 00:16:20,884
The caveat here being, our information is going to be different than your information

371
00:16:20,884 --> 00:16:22,084
no matter what game you're working on.

372
00:16:22,084 --> 00:16:26,104
Every group of players is going to be different and that's why you want to get to know them.

373
00:16:26,104 --> 00:16:32,226
The really important other thing here is that 70% of our spenders are female, which means

374
00:16:32,226 --> 00:16:35,946
that they have a very powerful voice when it comes to driving the success of our game.

375
00:16:35,946 --> 00:16:42,527
Our female players are the by and large largest spending group of all of the players, so their

376
00:16:42,527 --> 00:16:44,528
voice is very loud.

377
00:16:45,906 --> 00:16:47,888
So this is just for the visual learners in the group.

378
00:16:47,888 --> 00:16:50,211
It's sort of a re-representation

379
00:16:50,211 --> 00:16:53,115
and a quickly thrown together infographic

380
00:16:53,115 --> 00:16:57,180
to let you know some of the distribution data.

381
00:16:57,180 --> 00:16:59,443
So as I mentioned, I'll just point out

382
00:16:59,443 --> 00:17:03,468
that the current demographic data was added a week ago.

383
00:17:03,768 --> 00:17:05,691
the infographic was made a month ago.

384
00:17:05,691 --> 00:17:06,933
So it shifts a little bit.

385
00:17:06,933 --> 00:17:10,519
But we're sitting about 72% female players right now

386
00:17:10,519 --> 00:17:10,919
and 28% male.

387
00:17:10,919 --> 00:17:13,403
One of the interesting things for us

388
00:17:13,403 --> 00:17:18,251
is that we know that roughly 62% of our players

389
00:17:18,251 --> 00:17:19,112
are in North America.

390
00:17:20,353 --> 00:17:23,534
with a further 12% being in either the UK or Australia.

391
00:17:23,534 --> 00:17:26,815
And what that means for us is that we actually know that our players are very

392
00:17:26,815 --> 00:17:27,136
driven

393
00:17:27,136 --> 00:17:30,557
by, for lack of better terminology, Western ideology.

394
00:17:30,557 --> 00:17:35,979
They look at things through that lens, which means that we can deliver things using

395
00:17:35,979 --> 00:17:36,239
that lens.

396
00:17:36,239 --> 00:17:39,881
So how do we make that information matter?

397
00:17:39,881 --> 00:17:42,662
How do we use it? Australia Day.

398
00:17:43,979 --> 00:17:46,766
So using demographic data, we learned that there's actually

399
00:17:46,766 --> 00:17:49,372
a significant percent of players that are in Australia.

400
00:17:49,372 --> 00:17:51,197
Interestingly, when I say that 12% of the players

401
00:17:51,197 --> 00:17:53,362
are actually in either the UK or Australia.

402
00:17:54,760 --> 00:17:58,243
What we found out on top of that is 6% of our paying players

403
00:17:58,243 --> 00:17:59,384
are actually Australian.

404
00:17:59,384 --> 00:18:03,807
So Australian players really like investing in our game.

405
00:18:03,807 --> 00:18:06,409
And knowing that information allowed us to listen

406
00:18:06,409 --> 00:18:08,331
to feedback from players because players told us

407
00:18:08,331 --> 00:18:11,113
that for the last six years, they had been asking

408
00:18:11,113 --> 00:18:13,574
for some sort of celebration of Australia Day.

409
00:18:13,574 --> 00:18:15,896
But it had never been done because there never seemed

410
00:18:15,896 --> 00:18:18,358
to be any justification for it, right?

411
00:18:18,358 --> 00:18:21,040
It's a one-off, it's sort of a smaller group of people,

412
00:18:21,040 --> 00:18:22,101
why would we do it?

413
00:18:22,101 --> 00:18:22,862
Because.

414
00:18:22,942 --> 00:18:25,502
There's nothing wrong with Australians,

415
00:18:25,502 --> 00:18:26,863
just why would we do it?

416
00:18:26,863 --> 00:18:28,784
Because we tend to, as developers,

417
00:18:28,784 --> 00:18:31,384
target our largest groups first.

418
00:18:31,384 --> 00:18:33,385
But your small groups can have a voice too.

419
00:18:33,385 --> 00:18:35,226
And this is an instance in which we found out,

420
00:18:35,226 --> 00:18:37,566
well, if 6% of the players are Australian

421
00:18:37,566 --> 00:18:39,027
and they've been asking for something

422
00:18:39,027 --> 00:18:42,888
for the last six years, the odds are very, very good

423
00:18:42,888 --> 00:18:44,749
that it's going to perform well.

424
00:18:44,749 --> 00:18:46,890
And even if it doesn't perform well,

425
00:18:46,890 --> 00:18:49,771
we have run an experiment and disproven the theory

426
00:18:49,771 --> 00:18:52,031
that Australian-themed content can work.

427
00:18:53,112 --> 00:18:54,872
So what we did is we put together

428
00:18:54,872 --> 00:18:58,413
very basic Australia Day bundles,

429
00:18:58,413 --> 00:19:01,734
and you can see that this is a tiered bundle.

430
00:19:01,734 --> 00:19:05,275
Now I will note, while I talk about how important it is

431
00:19:05,275 --> 00:19:06,875
to treat your players like people,

432
00:19:06,875 --> 00:19:09,436
you will see pricing strategy up there.

433
00:19:09,436 --> 00:19:10,856
It's a reality of the business,

434
00:19:10,856 --> 00:19:13,177
so don't feel the need to call me out on it.

435
00:19:13,177 --> 00:19:16,558
But one of the things that we found

436
00:19:16,558 --> 00:19:19,378
is that they actually responded really well to tropes.

437
00:19:19,378 --> 00:19:21,379
So we asked them, what's Australian content?

438
00:19:21,379 --> 00:19:22,059
And they were like.

439
00:19:22,548 --> 00:19:24,431
give us whatever you think is Australian.

440
00:19:24,431 --> 00:19:27,055
They were very happy if you look at the platinum pack

441
00:19:27,055 --> 00:19:28,117
that they got a drop there.

442
00:19:28,117 --> 00:19:29,859
So that worked out really well for us.

443
00:19:31,606 --> 00:19:35,188
The next type of survey that we do is an engagement survey.

444
00:19:35,188 --> 00:19:40,872
And we actually use engagement surveys to survey players on the effectiveness of how we're engaging them,

445
00:19:40,872 --> 00:19:44,215
which is fairly simple to say but fairly difficult to do.

446
00:19:44,215 --> 00:19:48,478
We have a number of different engagement efforts that we actually make use of for our players.

447
00:19:48,478 --> 00:19:53,561
One of them is we do a weekly podcast where we just sit down and talk about the game,

448
00:19:53,561 --> 00:19:55,643
chat, and the players have an opportunity to get to know us better.

449
00:19:56,023 --> 00:19:58,564
We also run in-game contests for allowing players

450
00:19:58,564 --> 00:20:00,706
to create their own content for us.

451
00:20:00,706 --> 00:20:02,627
We also run in-game parties.

452
00:20:02,627 --> 00:20:04,468
Once a week, twice a week, players

453
00:20:04,468 --> 00:20:06,529
can sit down with members of our staff

454
00:20:06,529 --> 00:20:07,990
and just hang out in-game and socialize.

455
00:20:07,990 --> 00:20:10,972
So these are all sort of our engagement efforts.

456
00:20:10,972 --> 00:20:12,472
But any of these things that you're doing,

457
00:20:12,472 --> 00:20:15,574
you need to find a way to measure and make sure

458
00:20:15,574 --> 00:20:16,995
that they're actually being effective.

459
00:20:18,062 --> 00:20:19,783
One of the other things that we do for engagement surveys

460
00:20:19,783 --> 00:20:22,985
is we actually make use of quarterly report cards.

461
00:20:22,985 --> 00:20:24,726
So once every quarter, we send a report card out

462
00:20:24,726 --> 00:20:27,768
to the players and we ask them, based on these criteria,

463
00:20:27,768 --> 00:20:29,209
how are we performing this quarter?

464
00:20:29,209 --> 00:20:31,290
Are we better this quarter than we were last quarter,

465
00:20:31,290 --> 00:20:32,631
or are we worse?

466
00:20:32,631 --> 00:20:34,192
And they won't hesitate to tell you

467
00:20:34,192 --> 00:20:36,013
that you're doing a worse job than you were.

468
00:20:36,013 --> 00:20:38,595
And it's a really good way of keeping you honest, right?

469
00:20:38,595 --> 00:20:40,797
And knowing what your flaws are.

470
00:20:41,825 --> 00:20:45,009
And these actually have helped to drive our engagement significantly.

471
00:20:45,009 --> 00:20:49,394
One of the big takeaways that we had from one of our engagement surveys

472
00:20:49,394 --> 00:20:52,838
was that players liked the podcast, but listenership was down,

473
00:20:52,838 --> 00:20:54,280
and we couldn't figure out why.

474
00:20:54,280 --> 00:20:57,704
The format hadn't really changed, the quality hadn't really changed.

475
00:20:58,454 --> 00:20:59,695
So we didn't know why.

476
00:20:59,695 --> 00:21:02,216
So our philosophy is generally,

477
00:21:02,216 --> 00:21:03,277
if you don't know why, then ask.

478
00:21:03,277 --> 00:21:07,280
Because the players know, they're gonna tell you.

479
00:21:07,280 --> 00:21:10,402
We're very fortunate to have a highly engaged user base.

480
00:21:10,402 --> 00:21:13,223
So what we did is we sent out a survey and we said,

481
00:21:13,223 --> 00:21:14,984
what do you like about the Your World podcast

482
00:21:14,984 --> 00:21:15,805
and what don't you like?

483
00:21:15,805 --> 00:21:18,086
And one of the things that we learned is that,

484
00:21:18,863 --> 00:21:20,504
Over time, we've gotten very comfortable

485
00:21:20,504 --> 00:21:22,505
with the longer format for the podcast.

486
00:21:22,505 --> 00:21:25,587
The podcast, and the number sounds crazy to most people,

487
00:21:25,587 --> 00:21:28,068
ran between 45 minutes to an hour,

488
00:21:28,068 --> 00:21:30,169
which is a lot of time invested in podcasting,

489
00:21:30,169 --> 00:21:32,771
but they're a lot of fun to do, so whatever.

490
00:21:32,771 --> 00:21:34,191
But players provided the feedback

491
00:21:34,191 --> 00:21:35,452
that they wanted them to be shorter.

492
00:21:35,452 --> 00:21:39,234
And this is where the use of secondary feedback

493
00:21:39,234 --> 00:21:40,695
came in really handy.

494
00:21:40,695 --> 00:21:42,476
Because telling us that they want them shorter,

495
00:21:43,308 --> 00:21:46,251
isn't perfect, so we generally leave an area

496
00:21:46,251 --> 00:21:48,293
for subjective feedback so players can write it in,

497
00:21:48,293 --> 00:21:50,836
and the explanation that we got from players was brilliant.

498
00:21:50,836 --> 00:21:54,880
And their explanation was, I drive to work.

499
00:21:55,532 --> 00:21:58,272
and it takes about 10 to 15 minutes to drive to work.

500
00:21:58,272 --> 00:22:01,893
So I want the podcast to be between 10 and 15 minutes

501
00:22:01,893 --> 00:22:04,694
in length so when I get up the day that the podcast

502
00:22:04,694 --> 00:22:07,635
release I can get in the car, listen to the podcast,

503
00:22:07,635 --> 00:22:08,395
and drive to work.

504
00:22:08,395 --> 00:22:10,275
Awesome takeaway from players, right?

505
00:22:10,275 --> 00:22:13,296
Because what they told us is one, you're wasting your time.

506
00:22:13,296 --> 00:22:16,277
You know, you've got four people who are sort of involved

507
00:22:16,277 --> 00:22:17,557
in the whole podcast process.

