00:33:06,855 --> 00:33:09,955
the player innately had an understanding

766
00:33:09,955 --> 00:33:12,476
of the total cost of ownership of the theme.

767
00:33:13,096 --> 00:33:16,419
It just felt like it was costing more.

768
00:33:16,419 --> 00:33:17,740
And having that kind of feedback,

769
00:33:17,740 --> 00:33:19,221
having feedback from players where they're like,

770
00:33:19,221 --> 00:33:21,263
this doesn't feel the way it used to feel,

771
00:33:21,263 --> 00:33:22,804
sometimes it's right, sometimes it's wrong,

772
00:33:22,804 --> 00:33:23,925
but it's valuable to listen to.

773
00:33:25,530 --> 00:33:27,332
And finally, the player also said

774
00:33:27,332 --> 00:33:28,973
that we're doing too much of the same thing.

775
00:33:28,973 --> 00:33:30,934
If you take a look at the post, if you can find it,

776
00:33:30,934 --> 00:33:32,335
it's down near the bottom.

777
00:33:32,335 --> 00:33:35,377
Too many rugs, too many lamps, too many couches.

778
00:33:35,377 --> 00:33:36,217
That's great feedback.

779
00:33:36,217 --> 00:33:40,160
Because what that says to us, based on player feedback

780
00:33:40,160 --> 00:33:42,101
and there being supporting evidence from other players,

781
00:33:42,101 --> 00:33:43,362
is that we should be taking a look

782
00:33:43,362 --> 00:33:46,164
into our sales figures directly for those items

783
00:33:46,164 --> 00:33:47,384
and finding out whether or not

784
00:33:47,384 --> 00:33:48,585
their sales are on the decline.

785
00:33:48,585 --> 00:33:49,686
If they're on the decline,

786
00:33:49,686 --> 00:33:51,387
then we're wasting effort on doing them

787
00:33:51,387 --> 00:33:52,988
and we can be making better offerings

788
00:33:52,988 --> 00:33:54,269
that make the players happier.

789
00:33:54,609 --> 00:33:59,912
and make us generate more profit at the same time.

790
00:33:59,912 --> 00:34:03,714
So how do you get them to talk?

791
00:34:03,714 --> 00:34:06,335
Contrary to popular belief, not everybody wants to share their opinion

792
00:34:06,335 --> 00:34:08,497
and sometimes you have to encourage them to do so.

793
00:34:08,497 --> 00:34:12,499
So sometimes what we need to do is we actually need to incentivize our players

794
00:34:12,499 --> 00:34:13,819
to engage us in conversation.

795
00:34:13,819 --> 00:34:17,602
And sometimes we actually need to start that conversation ourselves.

796
00:34:18,717 --> 00:34:22,919
One of the things that I'll point out is that rewarding players is highly, highly effective.

797
00:34:22,919 --> 00:34:25,039
Rewards do not have to be large.

798
00:34:25,039 --> 00:34:27,440
They can be very small things.

799
00:34:27,440 --> 00:34:30,261
And a reward can be something as simple as a thank you.

800
00:34:30,261 --> 00:34:34,163
Just telling players that you appreciate the feedback and you're going to look into it

801
00:34:34,163 --> 00:34:37,244
is a reward for some people.

802
00:34:37,244 --> 00:34:41,505
But using rewards, I'll point out, our most normal survey response rates for games that

803
00:34:41,505 --> 00:34:43,106
we've worked on are about 40%.

804
00:34:44,541 --> 00:34:46,202
Which is, that's not bad.

805
00:34:46,202 --> 00:34:48,243
That's enough to get an idea.

806
00:34:48,243 --> 00:34:51,145
In your world, our average response rate is actually 63%.

807
00:34:51,145 --> 00:34:55,127
And that's because of the engagement effort.

808
00:34:55,127 --> 00:34:58,369
However, with rewards, our response rate goes up over 90%.

809
00:34:58,369 --> 00:35:01,130
For something as simple as an item

810
00:35:01,130 --> 00:35:03,431
that could take an artist an hour to make,

811
00:35:03,431 --> 00:35:05,673
all of a sudden we've increased the effectiveness

812
00:35:05,673 --> 00:35:07,073
of our data significantly.

813
00:35:07,073 --> 00:35:11,336
So here's an example of how we sort of showed off

814
00:35:11,336 --> 00:35:12,556
our newsletter to our players.

815
00:35:14,779 --> 00:35:16,861
And what we did, as you can see on the right-hand side,

816
00:35:16,861 --> 00:35:18,642
we incentivized it with a peacock hat,

817
00:35:18,642 --> 00:35:19,943
which is literally just a peacock

818
00:35:19,943 --> 00:35:22,105
that stands on top of your head.

819
00:35:22,105 --> 00:35:23,366
But players love the item,

820
00:35:23,366 --> 00:35:26,529
so the sign-up rate for our newsletter was over 70%,

821
00:35:26,529 --> 00:35:29,091
just through that incentivization.

822
00:35:29,091 --> 00:35:31,613
And the amazing thing about that for me

823
00:35:31,613 --> 00:35:35,316
is that we had created a separate channel of communication

824
00:35:35,316 --> 00:35:36,437
for players outside of the game,

825
00:35:36,437 --> 00:35:38,799
which is one of the biggest challenges everybody has,

826
00:35:38,799 --> 00:35:40,541
is how do you talk to them when they're not playing?

827
00:35:41,681 --> 00:35:45,785
Just as an aside, if you're gonna do a newsletter for your game,

828
00:35:45,785 --> 00:35:49,007
I highly encourage you not to make it

829
00:35:49,007 --> 00:35:52,550
a sales initiative. Make it about communicating with players.

830
00:35:52,550 --> 00:35:56,453
You can put sales stuff in there, but if you're only sending them another ad

831
00:35:56,453 --> 00:36:00,036
once a week to buy stuff, they're gonna unsubscribe really quickly.

832
00:36:02,792 --> 00:36:05,734
So rewarding player behavior is really important.

833
00:36:05,734 --> 00:36:08,335
We tend to use small tokens and character adornments

834
00:36:08,335 --> 00:36:10,757
because we find that they're highly effective.

835
00:36:10,757 --> 00:36:12,018
One of the things I like to compare it to

836
00:36:12,018 --> 00:36:14,460
is if you think about the Rock the Vote badges

837
00:36:14,460 --> 00:36:16,641
that you can get when you vote, it's the same idea.

838
00:36:16,641 --> 00:36:18,362
It's a way for people to let other people know

839
00:36:18,362 --> 00:36:21,164
that their voice was heard and that they contributed.

840
00:36:21,164 --> 00:36:23,526
So it doesn't, again, it doesn't have to be big.

841
00:36:23,526 --> 00:36:24,647
It can be something small.

842
00:36:24,647 --> 00:36:26,228
It's just a matter of making it.

843
00:36:26,228 --> 00:36:28,729
And especially if you make it exclusive,

844
00:36:28,729 --> 00:36:30,571
it's all the more valuable.

845
00:36:30,571 --> 00:36:30,751
Also,

846
00:36:31,480 --> 00:36:35,243
Always show your gratitude and appreciation for player feedback.

847
00:36:35,243 --> 00:36:36,645
Never stop saying thank you.

848
00:36:36,645 --> 00:36:42,790
Everything they have to say, even if it's terrible and mean and awful, is valuable.

849
00:36:42,790 --> 00:36:44,351
And I'll talk about that in just a sec.

850
00:36:44,351 --> 00:36:49,435
Most of the time, you also want to make sure that you're rewarding after and not before,

851
00:36:49,435 --> 00:36:50,876
which makes a ton of sense, right?

852
00:36:50,876 --> 00:36:55,460
If you want your kid to clean their room, you're not going to give them a chocolate bar before they clean the room.

853
00:36:55,460 --> 00:37:00,364
You're going to do it after, because otherwise you're just going to have a chocolated up kid in the dirty room.

854
00:37:01,159 --> 00:37:06,625
So here's an example of one of the ways that we use feedback

855
00:37:06,625 --> 00:37:08,267
in a sales context that we actually find very effective.

856
00:37:08,267 --> 00:37:11,710
And this is what we call a you asked, we listened.

857
00:37:11,710 --> 00:37:15,154
And this is part of a larger brand strategy

858
00:37:15,154 --> 00:37:17,276
that we use for the players to let them know

859
00:37:17,276 --> 00:37:18,898
that we're listening to their feedback.

860
00:37:19,914 --> 00:37:22,496
while also presenting them with items for sale.

861
00:37:22,496 --> 00:37:24,897
And this is a great scenario because

862
00:37:24,897 --> 00:37:26,499
if you look at the two hairs that are here,

863
00:37:26,499 --> 00:37:30,161
these are both player-designed hairs that we released.

864
00:37:30,161 --> 00:37:32,382
And the player feedback that we got was

865
00:37:32,382 --> 00:37:34,964
we would like more colors for these hairs, if you please.

866
00:37:34,964 --> 00:37:36,625
Because the color selection is great,

867
00:37:36,625 --> 00:37:38,026
but we think that there could be more.

868
00:37:39,547 --> 00:37:41,647
It's real hard to say no when people wanna buy

869
00:37:41,647 --> 00:37:44,928
more of your content, so we have a tendency to give in

870
00:37:44,928 --> 00:37:46,749
and just make that content for them.

871
00:37:46,749 --> 00:37:48,889
And then we'll package it up in one of these

872
00:37:48,889 --> 00:37:51,630
You Ask, We Listen, which is a standard format,

873
00:37:51,630 --> 00:37:53,471
and players respond really well to them.

874
00:37:53,471 --> 00:37:53,751
Sorry.

875
00:37:53,751 --> 00:37:58,472
So, how do we know that this works?

876
00:37:58,472 --> 00:38:02,373
It's a good question, Jacob, thank you.

877
00:38:02,373 --> 00:38:05,934
So, our DAU growth is currently about 30%

878
00:38:05,934 --> 00:38:06,855
of one-back players.

879
00:38:07,745 --> 00:38:09,625
And that's important to us,

880
00:38:09,625 --> 00:38:12,346
because the players that have grown

881
00:38:12,346 --> 00:38:13,946
our actual daily active users

882
00:38:13,946 --> 00:38:16,346
are players who used to play Yoville,

883
00:38:16,346 --> 00:38:17,327
got fed up and left,

884
00:38:17,327 --> 00:38:18,747
and then have heard from their friends

885
00:38:18,747 --> 00:38:20,847
that things have changed and things are better,

886
00:38:20,847 --> 00:38:22,067
so now it's time to come back.

887
00:38:22,067 --> 00:38:22,448
That's great,

888
00:38:22,448 --> 00:38:25,068
because these people also tend to be highly engaged players,

889
00:38:25,068 --> 00:38:26,528
and they're going to be contributing

890
00:38:26,528 --> 00:38:28,469
to the communication that we get back.

891
00:38:28,469 --> 00:38:30,029
Also on average, as I mentioned,

892
00:38:30,029 --> 00:38:33,390
the items that were created based on player feedback

893
00:38:33,390 --> 00:38:34,610
do perform 20% better,

894
00:38:34,610 --> 00:38:36,230
and our ARPDAU is up almost 40%.

895
00:38:37,115 --> 00:38:43,857
I can't go into direct numbers, but the product more than pays for itself, just by way of

896
00:38:43,857 --> 00:38:45,977
keeping communication open with players.

897
00:38:45,977 --> 00:38:52,018
So here's some of the added benefits to actually doing this.

898
00:38:52,018 --> 00:38:55,219
Caring can really help engage your players with your team.

899
00:38:55,219 --> 00:39:01,080
And more importantly, caring engages your team with your players, and that's a hard

900
00:39:01,080 --> 00:39:02,200
thing to do for some titles.

901
00:39:02,200 --> 00:39:05,340
How many people here work on a live ops title right now?

902
00:39:07,108 --> 00:39:09,690
So anybody who works on a LiveOps title knows

903
00:39:09,690 --> 00:39:11,751
that live operations can be a grind, right?

904
00:39:11,751 --> 00:39:13,612
Especially if you're highly content driven.

905
00:39:13,612 --> 00:39:16,574
It does sometimes feel like an unending treadmill.

906
00:39:16,574 --> 00:39:20,397
The way that you can break yourself out of that cycle

907
00:39:20,397 --> 00:39:22,498
is to find a way to communicate with your players

908
00:39:22,498 --> 00:39:23,399
and really care about them,

909
00:39:23,399 --> 00:39:26,200
because then you're making content for your friends, right?

910
00:39:26,200 --> 00:39:27,561
Then you're building stuff for people

911
00:39:27,561 --> 00:39:30,423
who love what you're doing and have your back as well.

912
00:39:30,423 --> 00:39:33,165
And that's a really good way to keep the flame burning

913
00:39:33,165 --> 00:39:36,307
between the team and yourself and the players.

914
00:39:37,688 --> 00:39:39,190
So this is one of our community managers.

915
00:39:39,190 --> 00:39:40,811
This is Trevor.

916
00:39:40,811 --> 00:39:45,595
Trevor is actually drinking coffee out of a mug that

917
00:39:45,595 --> 00:39:46,535
was sent to us by players.

918
00:39:46,535 --> 00:39:49,117
The postcard wall that you see behind him

919
00:39:49,117 --> 00:39:50,278
is all postcards sent by players.

920
00:39:50,278 --> 00:39:52,140
And the coffee in that mug is also coffee

921
00:39:52,140 --> 00:39:54,382
that was sent to us by players.

922
00:39:54,382 --> 00:39:55,603
Trevor's very brave.

923
00:39:55,603 --> 00:39:57,584
I wouldn't drink the coffee, but Trevor would.

924
00:39:57,584 --> 00:39:59,426
So good job, Trevor.

925
00:39:59,426 --> 00:40:02,828
How many community managers do we have in the room?

926
00:40:02,828 --> 00:40:03,008
Thank you.

927
00:40:05,569 --> 00:40:10,455
If anybody hasn't said that to you in the last month, I'm sorry. Thank you. Thank you so much for

928
00:40:10,455 --> 00:40:16,984
everything that you do. If you work with a community manager, thank them today. If you can't

929
00:40:16,984 --> 00:40:19,507
thank them today, thank them tomorrow, but thank them.

930
00:40:20,378 --> 00:40:22,479
of hard work that community managers do

931
00:40:22,479 --> 00:40:24,640
to bridge the gap between us and our players

932
00:40:24,640 --> 00:40:27,781
and provide that feedback in a meaningful context,

933
00:40:27,781 --> 00:40:29,502
while keeping a smile on their face

934
00:40:29,502 --> 00:40:33,504
and dealing with sometimes very frustrating situations

935
00:40:33,504 --> 00:40:34,124
is immeasurable.

936
00:40:34,124 --> 00:40:36,505
So make sure that you're thanking them.

937
00:40:36,505 --> 00:40:37,726
Give them a hug.

938
00:40:37,726 --> 00:40:38,987
They deserve it.

939
00:40:38,987 --> 00:40:42,228
So the takeaways for today.

940
00:40:42,228 --> 00:40:44,529
Number one, always remember the human side of gaming.

941
00:40:44,529 --> 00:40:46,610
One of the things I try to remind myself of,

942
00:40:46,610 --> 00:40:48,831
the first thing I do when I get into the office

943
00:40:48,831 --> 00:40:49,412
in the morning.

944
00:40:49,930 --> 00:40:52,914
is why did I start down this road?

945
00:40:52,914 --> 00:40:55,017
Why did I want to make video games?

946
00:40:55,017 --> 00:40:56,098
Because I love them.

947
00:40:56,098 --> 00:40:58,141
Okay, so why are people playing our games?

948
00:40:58,141 --> 00:40:59,062
Because they love them.

949
00:40:59,692 --> 00:41:01,252
They're not just another number on a spreadsheet.

950
00:41:01,252 --> 00:41:04,514
They're real, living, breathing people

951
00:41:04,514 --> 00:41:07,476
who are looking for an exciting and engaging experience

952
00:41:07,476 --> 00:41:09,777
that we can help deliver to them.

953
00:41:09,777 --> 00:41:13,199
And that will help drive your passion for building games

954
00:41:13,199 --> 00:41:15,160
for years if you can find a way to engage

955
00:41:15,160 --> 00:41:15,940
with players on that level.

956
00:41:15,940 --> 00:41:20,463
Also find out who your players are and what engages them.

957
00:41:20,463 --> 00:41:22,884
Don't make assumptions based on the data that you have.

958
00:41:22,884 --> 00:41:25,585
Actually ask them who they are, where they're from.

959
00:41:26,060 --> 00:41:29,663
what they did, as long as they love you.

960
00:41:29,663 --> 00:41:32,345
Also, create pillars and standards

961
00:41:32,345 --> 00:41:35,809
that you and your players will understand.

962
00:41:35,809 --> 00:41:37,130
And that's just for driving communication

963
00:41:37,130 --> 00:41:37,790
in an effective manner.

964
00:41:37,790 --> 00:41:42,294
So, behavior modeling is really important

965
00:41:42,294 --> 00:41:45,177
when it comes to dealing with player bases.

966
00:41:45,177 --> 00:41:46,878
So, if players are behaving in a way

967
00:41:46,878 --> 00:41:48,500
that is really admirable,

968
00:41:48,500 --> 00:41:49,881
make sure that you're rewarding that.

969
00:41:49,881 --> 00:41:51,983
If they're providing feedback to a survey,

970
00:41:51,983 --> 00:41:53,024
great, reward that.

971
00:41:53,284 --> 00:41:56,045
If you have one player that goes out of their way

972
00:41:56,045 --> 00:41:58,827
to help other players, it can be as simple

973
00:41:58,827 --> 00:42:00,407
as recognizing that and saying,

974
00:42:00,407 --> 00:42:02,849
this player's awesome, they do what we want them to do.

975
00:42:02,849 --> 00:42:05,490
That encourages the other players

976
00:42:05,490 --> 00:42:06,950
who are in the same, you know,

977
00:42:06,950 --> 00:42:08,231
who are sort of in the same situation

978
00:42:08,231 --> 00:42:10,212
and thinking of helping other people

979
00:42:10,212 --> 00:42:11,713
to take that next step and become helpful,

980
00:42:11,713 --> 00:42:12,833
and it drives community.

981
00:42:12,833 --> 00:42:15,094
Also make sure that you're making players

982
00:42:15,094 --> 00:42:16,695
a big part of the team.

983
00:42:16,695 --> 00:42:17,876
They have so much to offer.

984
00:42:17,876 --> 00:42:19,596
Don't leave that on the table.

985
00:42:21,980 --> 00:42:24,281
So, caveats, really important.

986
00:42:24,281 --> 00:42:29,824
Always remember that if you're engaging your players in an effective way, you're essentially

987
00:42:29,824 --> 00:42:31,405
giving them agency over your title.

988
00:42:31,405 --> 00:42:35,808
You're still going to be in charge, but they're helping drive that decision making.

989
00:42:35,808 --> 00:42:41,251
So agency can really easily breed passion, and passion can very easily be misinterpreted

990
00:42:41,251 --> 00:42:41,491
as anger.

991
00:42:43,444 --> 00:42:45,646
Make sure you're not taking it too personally

992
00:42:45,646 --> 00:42:47,307
and beware the vocal minority

993
00:42:47,307 --> 00:42:50,348
because they can break through if they really want to.

994
00:42:50,348 --> 00:42:53,610
And just maintain control of the conversation.

995
00:42:53,610 --> 00:42:55,792
Ultimately, you get to decide

996
00:42:55,792 --> 00:42:57,373
how you engage with your players.

997
00:42:57,373 --> 00:42:59,274
If people are being overly toxic,

998
00:42:59,274 --> 00:43:02,456
you don't have to continue to engage in that conversation.

999
00:43:02,456 --> 00:43:04,017
You can give them timeouts, it's okay.

1000
00:43:06,608 --> 00:43:09,355
Also find ways to keep the players busy and engaged.

1001
00:43:09,355 --> 00:43:11,481
One of the things that we found most effective

1002
00:43:11,481 --> 00:43:14,247
with engaging the players on a day-to-day basis.

1003
00:43:15,173 --> 00:43:18,615
is keeping them busy by way of games,

1004
00:43:18,615 --> 00:43:20,456
by way of social interaction,

1005
00:43:20,456 --> 00:43:22,337
and by way of designing stuff.

1006
00:43:22,337 --> 00:43:25,479
And what that does is it takes away

1007
00:43:25,479 --> 00:43:26,600
the potential for boredom.

1008
00:43:26,600 --> 00:43:28,221
If they're in an idle state

1009
00:43:28,221 --> 00:43:29,541
and they're not actively playing the game,

1010
00:43:29,541 --> 00:43:31,983
but they are still interacting with the community,

1011
00:43:31,983 --> 00:43:34,644
boredom can sometimes feed drama

1012
00:43:34,644 --> 00:43:37,306
because they're bored and they're looking to start a fight

1013
00:43:37,306 --> 00:43:39,627
because they're looking to be entertained by anything.

1014
00:43:39,627 --> 00:43:41,988
So if you're finding ways to keep them entertained,

1015
00:43:41,988 --> 00:43:43,549
you're gonna nip that in the bud right away.

1016
00:43:44,033 --> 00:43:46,597
Don't take feedback personally.

1017
00:43:46,597 --> 00:43:51,264
As hard as it possibly is, try not to take feedback personally.

1018
00:43:51,264 --> 00:43:53,968
One of the challenging things, quite frankly,

